## Diagnosis

The `micro` rendering mode was introduced as a "clever" progressive-disclosure pattern: as tiles shrink, font size degrades from normal → small → `micro` (8 px). The intent was to always show *something*, but 8 px text is below the threshold of legibility for any real user (~11–12 px minimum) and below WCAG's practical floor. The result is rendered text that cannot actually be read — it provides the illusion of information without the substance.

## Root Cause

**AP-072 – Illegible Micro-Typography as a Progressive Disclosure Fallback**

The anti-pattern: using font scaling as the *sole* mechanism to handle constrained space, continuing to render text even when the container is too small for legible type. The correct primitive is **visibility**, not **size** — hide text below the legibility threshold, don't shrink it past it.

---

## Fix

### 1. Remove the `micro` size tier entirely from the tile renderer

```tsx
// components/knowledge/KnowledgeTreemap/TreemapTile.tsx  (before)

type RenderMode = 'full' | 'compact' | 'micro';

function getRenderMode(width: number, height: number): RenderMode {
  const area = width * height;
  if (area < 1024 || width < 32) return 'micro';   // ← the offender
  if (area < 4096 || width < 80) return 'compact';
  return 'full';
}

// …inside the tile JSX:
{mode === 'full'    && <FullLabel   name={name} count={count} />}
{mode === 'compact' && <CompactLabel name={name} />}
{mode === 'micro'   && (
  <span className="text-[8px] leading-none truncate">{name}</span>  // ← remove
)}
```

```tsx
// components/knowledge/KnowledgeTreemap/TreemapTile.tsx  (after)

// No 'micro' tier — two tiers only, or nothing.
type RenderMode = 'full' | 'compact' | 'hidden';

// Legibility floor: don't render text if the tile can't hold it.
// 48 px wide × 24 px tall is roughly the minimum for a single truncated word
// at the design system's smallest sanctioned size (text-xs / 12px + padding).
const LABEL_MIN_WIDTH  = 48;  // px
const LABEL_MIN_HEIGHT = 24;  // px

function getRenderMode(width: number, height: number): RenderMode {
  if (width < LABEL_MIN_WIDTH || height < LABEL_MIN_HEIGHT) return 'hidden';
  if (width < 80 || height < 40) return 'compact';
  return 'full';
}
```

### 2. Replace the micro render branch with a tooltip-bearing silent tile

```tsx
// TreemapTile.tsx — JSX

export function TreemapTile({ x, y, width, height, name, count, href }: TreemapTileProps) {
  const mode = getRenderMode(width, height);

  return (
    <Tooltip content={`${name} (${count})`} side="top">
      {/* Tooltip always fires on hover regardless of mode — no information lost */}
      <Link
        href={href}
        style={{ left: x, top: y, width, height }}
        className={cn(
          'absolute overflow-hidden rounded-sm',
          'focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-brand-500',
          // Give tiny tiles a visible border so they're discoverable
          mode === 'hidden' ? 'border border-surface-200/40' : '',
        )}
        aria-label={`${name}, ${count} items`}  // always present for a11y
      >
        {mode === 'full' && (
          <div className="flex h-full flex-col justify-between p-2">
            <span className="text-xs font-medium leading-tight text-content-primary truncate">
              {name}
            </span>
            <span className="text-xs text-content-secondary tabular-nums">
              {count}
            </span>
          </div>
        )}

        {mode === 'compact' && (
          <div className="flex h-full items-center px-1.5">
            <span className="text-xs font-medium leading-none text-content-primary truncate">
              {name}
            </span>
          </div>
        )}

        {/* mode === 'hidden': no text rendered — tooltip carries the label */}
      </Link>
    </Tooltip>
  );
}
```

### 3. Ensure the constants live in one place (single source of truth)

```ts
// components/knowledge/KnowledgeTreemap/constants.ts

/** Minimum tile dimensions that can hold a legible label (text-xs / 12 px). */
export const TILE_LABEL_MIN_WIDTH  = 48; // px
export const TILE_LABEL_MIN_HEIGHT = 24; // px

/**
 * Below this width a tile shows no text and relies solely on the hover
 * tooltip + aria-label for its identity.
 */
export const TILE_COMPACT_MIN_WIDTH = 80; // px
```

Import these in both `TreemapTile.tsx` and any snapshot/storybook tests so the threshold is never duplicated.

### 4. Update Storybook stories to cover the boundary

```tsx
// stories/KnowledgeTreemap.stories.tsx

export const TinyTile: Story = {
  args: { width: 32, height: 20, name: 'Rust', count: 4, href: '/tag/rust' },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    // Text must NOT appear in the DOM for tiny tiles
    expect(canvas.queryByText('Rust')).toBeNull();
    // aria-label must still be present
    expect(canvas.getByRole('link', { name: /Rust, 4 items/i })).toBeInTheDocument();
  },
};

export const CompactTile: Story = {
  args: { width: 60, height: 30, name: 'Rust', count: 4, href: '/tag/rust' },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const label = canvas.getByText('Rust');
    // Must be rendered at text-xs (12 px), never below
    expect(label).toHaveClass('text-xs');
  },
};
```

---

## Principle

> **Never use font size as a graceful-degradation axis below the legibility floor.**
>
> Text either fits at a sanctioned size or it does not appear. When it cannot appear, a non-visual channel (tooltip, `aria-label`, `title`) carries the information instead. Rendered-but-unreadable text is strictly worse than no text: it consumes visual space, creates noise, and breaks the accessibility contract by presenting content that assistive technology reads aloud at normal volume while sighted users see a 8 px smear.

The concrete rule for this system:

| Tile width | Label behaviour |
|---|---|
| ≥ 80 px | Full label (`text-xs` minimum, `text-sm` if height allows) |
| 48 – 79 px | Compact label (`text-xs`, name only, truncated) |
| < 48 px | **No rendered text.** Tooltip + `aria-label` only. |

Add this table to the Elan component spec for `Treemap` so reviewers have a concrete rule to cite in PR feedback.
